    "title": "Inspection & verification",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "What this group is",
        "body": "This category is the last line of checks before product reaches a patient: machines that inspect and verify every finished unit. Automated visual inspection looks at filled vials and syringes for particles, cracks, and fill defects; a container-closure integrity tester proves each container is properly sealed against contamination; and a checkweigher weighs every unit to confirm it holds the right amount. They are the automated equivalent of a careful final examination, done at production speed on 100% of units."
      },
      {
        "title": "Why qualification turns on detection, not just measurement",
        "body": "Unlike a process machine, an inspection machine's job is to catch the bad units and pass the good ones - so qualifying it is about proving its detection works. That means challenging it with known defects (and known-good units) and showing it reliably rejects the defects while not over-rejecting good product. The key is detection reliability and the correct setting of accept/reject limits, because a missed defect can reach a patient and an over-sensitive machine scraps good product."
      }
    ],
